<!-- ── SCA ORGANIZATION SPOTLIGHT ── -->
<div class="spotlight">
  <div class="section-label">Organization Spotlight</div>
  <div class="card-title" style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1.2rem;margin-bottom:10px;">Student Conservation Association (SCA)</div>
  <p>If you are interested in environmental policy, federal land management, or just want a way into federal service that most political science students overlook, SCA deserves your attention. Founded in 1957, SCA is the largest provider of hands-on conservation programs for young adults in the country — placing people 18 and older into internships at national parks, forests, wildlife refuges, and cultural landmarks through partnerships with the National Park Service, U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service, Bureau of Land Management, and U.S. Forest Service.</p>
  <p>Positions range from backcountry patrol and ecological surveys to <strong>cultural resource management and visitor services</strong> — the latter two being the most natural fits for political science students. Most positions include a paid living allowance, housing, and an AmeriCorps education award. Many also confer <strong>federal hiring eligibility</strong>, which is a meaningful long-term career advantage if you are at all interested in working in the federal government.</p>
  <p>SCA no longer requires a membership fee to apply. The portal lists dozens of open positions at any given time with individual closing dates. The best strategy: apply to 8–10 positions to maximize your odds. One current example posting: <strong>AmeriCorps Cultural Resources Management Member at Navajo National Monument</strong> (June–October 2026, $700/week + $1,000/month housing allowance + AmeriCorps education award).</p>
  <a href="https://thesca.org/serve/opportunities" target="_blank">Search Open Positions →</a>
  &nbsp;&nbsp;
  <a href="https://thesca.org/faqs" target="_blank">FAQ →</a>
  &nbsp;&nbsp;
  <a href="https://www.mobilizegreen.org/internships" target="_blank">Also See: MobilizeGreen →</a>
</div>


